===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} ''[[tun|tūn]]'' 'enclosure, village', from {{proto|Germanic}} *''tunaz, tunan'' (cf. Dutch ''[[tuin]]'' ‘garden’, German ''[[Zaun]]'' 'fence', Danish/Swedish ''[[tun]]'' ‘fence’), from Gaulish ''dunon'' 'hill; hillfort' (cf. Welsh ''din'' 'hill', Irish ''dún'' 'fortress'), from {{proto|Indo-European}} *''dheue'' 'to finish, come full circle' or *''dhwene'' (cf. Latin ''fūnus'' 'burial', Hittite ''tuhhušta'' 'it is finished', Ancient Greek ''thnētós'' 'mortal', ''thánatos'' 'death', ''thaneīn'' 'to die', Sanskrit ''ádhvanīt'' 'he vanished').

